### Step 1: Setup Your React Project with Capacitor

First, ensure you have a React project set up with Capacitor. If you haven't already, you can create a new project using the following command:

```bash
npx @capacitor/cli init myApp
cd myApp
npm install @capacitor/react @capacitor/core @capacitor/cli
```

### Step 2: Create a Network Status Component

Create a new React component that will handle the network status. This component will use the `NetworkInformation` API to detect the network status and update the UI accordingly.

```jsx
import React, { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

const NetworkStatus = () => {
  const [isOnline, setIsOnline] = useState(navigator.onLine);

  useEffect(() => {
    const handleNetworkStatusChange = () => {
      setIsOnline(navigator.onLine);
    };

    const networkStatusListener = navigator.onLine ? () => {} : navigator.addEventListener('online', handleNetworkStatusChange);

    return () => {
      navigator.removeEventListener('online', networkStatusListener);
    };
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Network Status: {isOnline ? 'Online' : 'Offline'}</p>
    </div>
  );
};

export default NetworkStatus;
```

### Step 3: Integrate the Network Status Component

Now, integrate the `NetworkStatus` component into your application. You can place it anywhere in your app where you want to display the network status.

```jsx
