In Rust, you can use the `clipboard` crate to interact with the system clipboard. To get a notification when the clipboard content changes and print the current value, you can use a combination of the `clipboard` crate and a platform-specific event loop. Here's an example using the `gtk` crate for a cross-platform solution:

First, add the required dependencies to your `Cargo.toml`:

```toml
[dependencies]
clipboard = "0.5.0"
gtk = { version = "0.9.2", features = ["v3_16"] }
```

Next, create a new Rust file (e.g., `main.rs`) and add the following code:

```rust
use clipboard::{Clipboard, ClipboardProvider};
use gtk::{
    glib::{ConnectFlags, MainContext, MainLoop, Signal},
    prelude::*,
};

fn main() {
    let application = gtk::Application::new(
        Some("com.example.clipboard_watcher"),
        Default::default(),
    )
    .expect("Initialization failed");

    application.connect_activate(|app| {
        let clipboard = Clipboard::get(&app.get_default_display()).expect("Failed to get clipboard");

        let main_context = MainContext::default();
        let main_loop = MainLoop::new(Some(&main_context), &[]);

        let clipboard_watcher = ClipboardWatcher::new(clipboard, main_context.clone());

        clipboard_watcher.connect_changed(|clipboard| {
            let text = clipboard.get_text().expect("Failed to get clipboard text");
            println!("Clipboard changed: {}", text);
        });

        main_loop.run();
    });

    application.run(&[]);
}

struct ClipboardWatcher {
    clipboard: Clipboard,
    main_context: MainContext,
}

impl ClipboardWatcher {
    fn new(clipboard: Clipboard, main_context: MainContext) -> Self {
        let watcher = ClipboardWatcher { clipboard, main_context };
        watcher.start_watching();
        watcher
    }

    fn start_watching(&self) {
        let clipboard = self.clipboard.clone();
        let main_context = self.main_context.clone();

        let signal = Signal::new(
            &clipboard,
            "owner-change",
            (),
            ConnectFlags::after(),
            move |clipboard| {
                main_context.iteration(true);

                if let Ok(text) = clipboard.get_text() {
                    println!("Clipboard changed: {}", text);
                }
            },
        );

        signal.connect(&clipboard);
    }

    fn connect_changed<F>(&self, f: F)
    where
        F: FnMut(&Clipboard) + 'static,
    {
        let clipboard = self.clipboard.clone();
        let main_context = self.main_context.clone();

        let signal = Signal::new(
            &clipboard,
            "owner-change",
            (),
            ConnectFlags::after(),
            move |clipboard| {
                main_context.iteration(true);
                f(clipboard);
            },
        );

        signal.connect(&clipboard);
    }
}
```

This example creates a `ClipboardWatcher` struct that listens for clipboard changes using the `owner-change` signal and prints the current clipboard value when it changes. The `gtk` crate is used to create an event loop that allows the application to wait for clipboard changes.

