```bash
docker-compose exec db mysql -u root -p
```

Enter the root password when prompted.

```sql
CREATE DATABASE mydb;
CREATE USER 'user'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'password';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON mydb.* TO 'user'@'localhost';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
EXIT;
```

7. Start the Docker Compose services:

```bash
docker-compose up -d
```

8. Generate SSL certificates for your domain using certbot:

```bash
docker-compose exec certbot certonly --webroot --webroot-path=/var/www/certbot --email your-email@example.com --agree-tos --no-eff-email --force-renewal -d yourdomain.com -d www.yourdomain.com
```

9. Configure Nginx to use SSL certificates:

Edit the `nginx.conf` file and add the following server block for HTTPS:

```nginx
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name yourdomain.com www.yourdomain.com;

    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/privkey.pem;

    # ... rest of the configuration
}
```

10. Restart the Docker Compose services:

```bash
docker-compose restart
```

Now, your Docker Compose server with Nginx, Letsencrypt certbot, PHP 8.1, and MariaDB should be up and running.

